#Text=Edward
#Text=Phelips ( speaker )
#Text=Sir Edward Phelips , by unknown artist
#Text=Arms of Phelips : Argent , a chevron gules between three roses of the second seeded or barbed vert
#Text=Sir Edward Phelips ( ca .

#Text=1555/1560 – 1614 ) was an English lawyer and politician , the Speaker of the English House of Commons from 1604 until 1611 , and subsequently Master of the Rolls from 1611 until his death in 1614 .
#Text=He was an elected MP from 1584 , and in 1588 , following a successful career as a lawyer , he commissioned Montacute House to be built as a Summer house for himself and his family .
#Text=He was knighted in 1603 [ 1 ] and one of his major roles was as the opening prosecutor during the trial of the Gunpowder Plotters . [ 2 ]
#Text=He married Margaret Newdigate , and his son , Sir Robert Phelips , inherited his land and property . [ 3 ]
#Text=Life
#Text=He was fourth and youngest son of Thomas Phelips ( 1500 – 1588 ) of Montacute , Somerset , by his wife Elizabeth ( d. 1598 ) , daughter of John Smythe of Long Ashton in the same county .
#Text=His father stood godfather to Thomas Coryate .
#Text=Edward was born about 1560 : according to Coryate , who refers to him as a patron , he was about 53 in 1613 . [ 4 ]
#Text=He joined the Middle Temple , where he was autumn reader in 1596 .
#Text=In 1584 he entered parliament as MP for Bere Alston , followed by terms as MP for Weymouth and Melcombe Regis in 1586 , Penryn in 1593 and Andover in 1597 .
#Text=In 1601 he was elected knight of the shire for Somerset .
#Text=On 11 February 1603 he was named serjeant-at-law , but Queen Elizabeth died , and he did not proceed to his degree until the following reign .
#Text=On 17 May he was made king 's serjeant and knighted .
#Text=In November he took part in the trial of Sir Walter Raleigh .
#Text=He was re-elected to parliament for Somerset on 11 February 1604 , and on 19 March was elected speaker .
#Text=According to Sir Julius Cæsar , he was the best speaker for some decades , and although long-winded , did expedite some business for the king . [ 4 ]
#Text=On 17 July 1604 he was granted the office of justice of common pleas in the county palatine of Lancaster .
#Text=In this capacity he was very active against Catholics ; he is said to have declared that , as the law stood , all who were present when mass was celebrated were guilty of felony .
#Text=He was one of those appointed to examine the Gunpowder Plot conspirators , and in January 1606 opened the indictment against Guy Fawkes .
#Text=He was also chancellor to Henry Frederick , Prince of Wales .
#Text=On 2 December 1608 he was granted the reversion of the mastership of the rolls , but did not succeed to the office until January 1611 .
#Text=On 14 July 1613 he was appointed ranger of all royal forests , parks , and chases in England . [ 4 ]

#Text=Besides his London house in Chancery Lane , and another at Wanstead , Essex , where he entertained the king , Phelips built a large mansion in Somerset , Montacute House , which is still standing , and in the possession of the National Trust .

#Text=He died on 11 September 1614 , having married , firstly , Margaret ( d. 28 April 1590 ) , daughter of Robert Newdegate of Newdegate , Surrey , by whom he had two sons , Sir Robert and Francis ; secondly , Elizabeth ( d. 26 March 1638 ) , daughter of Thomas Pigott of Doddershall House , Buckinghamshire . [ 4 ]
#Text=Parliamentary convention
#Text=the 2d of April , 1604 , rule .
#Text=That a question being once made , and carried in the affirmative or negative , cannot be questioned again , but must stand as judgment of the House .
#Text=...
#Text=...
#Text=On the 1st of June , 1610 , agreed for a rule .
#Text=That no Bill of the same substance can be brought in the same session .
#Text=— John Hatsell , Rules of Proceeding , in Precedents of proceedings in the House of Commons : with observations [ 5 ]

#Text=It was under Phelips that the " 1604 rule " was established : a parliamentary convention that " no motion can be put by the Government to the Commons twice in the same parliamentary session if the wording is exactly or substantially the same .
